```

<hr />

One thing I noticed is that the pairing seems to be working fine if we scan/initiate pairing from the login screen (without logging into any profile).

From the video, @pavloburykh has initiated pairing from another profile.

> These last two logs are interesting, `{:type "transfer-success", :action 4}}` means that the pairing process should be complete. However `Initiated local pairing` is called after
> 
> ```
> 09-13 12:14:28.943 11089 11421 I ReactNativeJS: INFO [status-im.signals.core:33] - local pairing signal received {:event {:type "transfer-success", :action 4}}
> 09-13 12:14:28.946 11089 11421 I ReactNativeJS: INFO [status-im2.contexts.syncing.events:70] - Initiated local pairing {:response "{\"error\":\"\"}", :event :syncing/input-connection-string-for-bootstrapping}
> ```

@Samyoul - `Initiated local pairing {:response "{\"error\":\"\"}", :event :syncing/input-connection-string-for-bootstrapping}` is the log from the callback of `InputConnectionStringForBootstrapping`. The `Initiated local pairing` text is misleading. Apologies for that.

@churik @Samyoul it turned out that in this case syncing works as expected when users are logged in the same account. I just wasn't aware that we are supporting this flow. 

> I wonder if the fix for this issue is to introduce a check that the account being synced matches the account the user is logged into. Then return an error if the user tries to sync and pair an other account while still logged in.

@Samyoul agree, that would be the right fix.
